{"id":14881489,"mediaExerciseId":"a656d675-450c-49e4-a277-18c7dff56006","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"14","chapterTitle":"Cost of Capital","groupId":612390,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":494,"solutions":[{"id":6440856,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will determine whether there will be potential problems when we use the specific company as a pure play company for the other company. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A pure play company refers to a company that specializes on only one specific line of business. This means that the services provided by the company are not diversified. \n\nIn the case of TSLA, it is a pure play company since it focuses primarily in automobiles currently. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"However, we cannot use TSLA to estimate the cost of capital for SMI for a variety of reasons.\n\nFirstly, the nature of the products sold by the companies differ in price point. TSLA is known to sell automobiles at a high price point while SMI is at the lower end. This already creates a problem in estimating the cost of capital for SMI.\n\nAside from that, TSLA is a publicly traded company while SMI is private. This means that TSLA is able to release bonds to increase their capital which also alters the estimation for SMI. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"dc457cc1-3103-4f27-8901-f1311779a090","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq